text: When are you guys going to realize that a movie adaption of a book, is going to be different than what you're expecting.   Everyone has different imaginations, look at this as Robert's imagination of the book. The way he wants the movie to flow, is something Veronica has accepted and gave her consent to already.   My bet is that the box you all are hating against, is the hard drive they're fighting to get, containing Edith Prior's video and revelation of the past and how it all started. Why is it a box? Because this is an action movie for teenagers and young adults, so if you see it in a different perspective, they would like to make it have a unique appearance.   The most important thing is the plot, and how it should stay true to the book as much as possible. And if you pay close attention to every single detail of the trailer (appearance excluded), almost everything is there. The hard drive which caused it all, the brother being a traitor, Peter joining the Erudite, FourTris scenes, Christina's heartbreak when she finds out about the truth, and last but not least, the whole deal between Tris and Jeanine.   So try to be a little bit more open minded, guys. Divergent was already different from the book, so you can't really expect Insurgent to do the opposite, when it has so much more events going on.   PS: Edgar is NOT someone who will interfere FourTris' relationship in the movie. Veronica confirmed it herself during her booth in CCSD. So no, there's no love triangle when it comes to FourTris.

Second: I can see a lot of similarities. Don't be bitching saying: THIS IS NOTHING LIKE THE BOOK! Because it has its moments (Tris, Caleb and Four leaving the Amity compound), (Evelyn as factionless leader and Johanna, they didn't cut them), (Eric's speech before he dies), (Marlene's death), (Christina completely sad about Tris killing Will), (the factualness look amazing), (Caleb's betrayal), (TRIS VS TRIS, fuck I wanted to see it so bad!!), (Jeanine experiments). It IS like the book in its ways, books do not work like movies. You are supposed to tell a 520 page book in 2h30min maximum.  Last thing: You can not judge something completely by the trailers. I mean, you saw Tris shooting a gun, but what if someone's in front of her and she can't shoot? You're seriously missing your point. For what I saw, they turned the series much more intense, mature and action-packed, this will make the series get recognition for the last movies, and you will care more about Tris. If you're not going to be supportive and help your book series adaptation become famous, please, stop bitching and hating about it.

text: So I found this comment on this news page, and i think the person who wrote it have a good explanation of what's up with that box: "The box is simply a physical version of "the information" aka the Edith Prior video. In the video we find out that after a level of divergence reaches it's limit, the video must be revealed and those divergent must travel outside the fence to meet with the people who created this experiment. In the movie, the box will probably have some sort of tape inside or projection of the video, but to open this, someone with a level of divergence enough for 3 faction aptitudes must open it somehow, that's why Tris is "the one" and that's why there are other divergent people who appear in the trailer but didn't have the aptitude for 3 factions, only for two (the symbols that lit up), and couldn't open the box. This would make sense because the video would come just in time for that certain level of divergence to reach it's limits and for people to have to go outside the fence, also Tris mentions Jeanine has an IDEA of what's inside the box, so the only difference from the book to the movie is that in the book, Jeanine has watched the Edith Prior video, in the movie, she'll only have an idea of what it is."  Link to the page with the comment¬†http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/insurgent-trailer-what-is-up-756899

text: okay im here to give my opinion on the trailer, ive got to admit the trailer wasn't 100% true to the book but its not 100% not true to the book. They do include A LOT from what happened in the book but thats sadly being overlooked by the negative, The only parts that were wrong to me were  1. How she can shoot a gun with no problem, in the book shes not able to use a gun cause of will.  2. The odd box, BUT I THINK I HAVE A THEORY OF THE BOX! Since the box is something we see throughout the trailer it obvious has relevance in the movie, i think thats going to be the usb that tris gets and the edith prior information is kept on, i know what you guys are thinking "how could that be the usb its huge" it either might be the usb or contain the usb in it??   honestly other then that i don't see anything wrong, obviously they made certain things a lot more exaggerated then they were in divergent, for example the trains look a lot bigger and military grade, the factionless are located in a huge factory and the way the simulations are entered with (the wires)  In my opinion the wires were a lot cooler, im pretty sure the producers didn't want the old boring needle and fluid. They producers might have wanted to enhance everything in this movie to make it a bigger and better action packed movie.  I have faith in this movie and i love the series and am NOT giving up on this movie. If you think of it they are just improving the story line with alot more epic settings, a lot more action, and sure they change some things but they just replaced the changed things, not got rid of it completely. text: Granted, trailers do no justice to a movie hardly ever. I understand how the experience in a book is different from a movie (because your not in the main characters mind, you're watching as if you were an on-looker in a sense), and I also understand the time constraints an stuff, so some things have to be cut, but when the heck has there ever been this box thing in the book?? I can even understand adding more action or whatever (because things transfer differently from book to screen) but adding new things that totally change the plot?? I see things I recognize from the book, but then totally new stuff is added. There was never a box!¬†  I'm still very open to watching the movie, but I'll have to erase everything I know from the book and watch it as if it was just a movie in itself. Looking at it as only a movie, with no book history, it still looks good and interesting, and I still want to give it a chance. Its just annoying they felt they needed to add stuff, but maybe they'll make it work out somehow, like I mentioned, trailers hardly do justice whether the movie is good or bad. :)

text: Adaptations will always have changes from the original media. Some are justified, some do not make sense, others simply increase in number and magnitude the action scenes. I am already used to it and I can (sort of) have fun with book adaptations at the theaters. The big problem is when adaptation modifies the characters in itself. I'm not talking about the physical aspects but of their personality, their motivations. I liked the adaptation of Divergent. The book in itself is the best of the series, maybe that's why the changes have been superficial. The most significant, the change of fear simulations, changing somewhat the characteristic of the Dauntless (they seem more Erudites in the simulations, strategically thinking a way to escape the situation, no really related to bravery), but it was "ok". The trailer for Insurgent, suggests that this film certainly they changed the motivations of certain characters.  (A LOT OF SPOILERS AHEAD) The clearest example is Jeanine. In the books, she knows what is kept secret by Abnegation. Marcus suggests that he shared the information with the former leader of the Erudite, which in his turn informed Jeanine. The motivation for hunting divergents is to prevent the situation described by Edith Prior (a increased population of divergents) do not modify the structure of the city's society. The motivation of the attack directed at Abnegation is to prevent the information from becoming public (just as the previous attacks, via newspapers, was to make the members of Abnegation unreliable). The box in the Insurgent trailer could even be a really cool idea, but dramatically modified Jeanine's motivations as it means: 1. No one knew the information, not even the leaders of Abnegation (perhaps only Tris¬¥s mom). 2. Jeanine had no reason to hunt the divergents, except now she is looking for the "ideal divergent" (which should be someone who is a GP) to open the box. Completely different from the book, where she is looking for a way to control them via simulation. 3. Kill divergents seem an unusual way if you're behind one of them to reveal a secret information, which means that Jeanine did not know before the attack she would need a divergent to get to it (or she is not so "erudite" after all). 4. Jeanine really needed to spend years accusing Abnegation and make a military attack only to find a confidential information? This seems practicable? SO Jeanine is a completely different character in the film.  I hope that is at least fun to watch.

text: In the Divergent books Tobias and Tris talk about how they don't feel comfortable with sex and they set limits for their physical relationship...and Lionsgate is like "Hey! How about we ADD sex scenes to a movie aimed for teenagers?! Let's just make it more inappropriate and ignore the books! YAY!". The fact that FourTris actually set limits is one of the reasons I loved the series - they didn't just sleep together after knowing each other for a day like in other popular teen series. I don't know. Maybe most teens don't care about this kind of thing, but there are already so many books I can't read, movies I can't watch, and music I can't listen to because of unnecessary language, violence, and sexual scenes. Divergent was one of the few book series aimed for teenagers that I actually felt comfortable reading. I was very sad when I saw that they completely got rid of that for the films. Am I the only one who feels this way?

text: Reading through the comments and seeing what I totally agree and disagree with has been interesting. I've read all the books, I saw the first showing of the damn movie when It came out wearing my fanmade merch and everything, I don't know what this piece of shit is. Honestly. Yes the same characters, similar universe. But this is not okay. In any way. People opinion that it got changed up because the last book is pretty much boring in most opinions. I don't give a damn how shitty the book was, if you're going to make a movie adaption to a series that has thousands of fans already make sure you don't add in any nonsense. What the hell is that box for? Last time I read Insurgent they were testing on Tris to find out how to CONTROL stronger divergents not to crack a stupid box. Are they even going to talk about the secret thats literally revealed the last page of insurgent? I will rant all I want. The producers have made me angry. I'm not saying I could make the perfect movie adaption but it sure as hell wouldn't add a box that the readers have no fucking clue about. This makes me so angry and why are people so excited about it? text: The appeal of the book is what should be shown in the movie. The books are amazing, and so different to every other book or movie i've read or seen. The whole appeal of the Divergent series is that it's very unique and gives a sort of vibe that seems realistic with the circumstances of characters. A vibe that i've never felt reading or watching any other book or film because it wouldn't be relative or make sense with the plot. Watching this trailer completely eliminated that vibe. Maybe this trailer did a terrible job of depicting the whole movie, but from the trailer, i can say that the vibe it gives me is very neutral, or below neutral, because it seems like just any other action film, but Divergent was a brilliant idea that was communicated well through the books, and had the film been as close to the book as possible, that brilliant idea could be communicated well through the film to those who have and have not read the books. Tis a shame, i've been waiting for almost 2 years. Allegiant better not disappoint because that's the one i'm really looking forward to. My tip: capture the essence of the book which create the perfect vibe of the book, and somehow, with Veronica Roth's help, put that into the film.¬†

text: The trailer doesn't at all really have anything to do with the book. They just are not alike whatsoever, of course there is more to the movie but I would have at least HOPED that I would get to see some parts from oh I dunno... THE BOOK!! The trailer could have at least featured event from the book! Most of this was pretty inaccurate. Let me explain of couple of things just so people that actually haven't read the books (shame...) will know what I'm talking about:  #1.¬†First off what the HECK is that box?!?!?! Yes, yes they did explain in the trailer (not the book) that this box was to test out Divergents or something to see if they can open it. Yes it is known that nobody (including Jeanine) knows what the heck is inside of the box. But this had nothing to do with the book and left me¬†a little confused and with lots of questions (suspense is good =, but not suspenseful questions). If they were going to focus a movie on a thing that never even happen in the book it was based off of at LEAST explain a little better what the heck that thing is! ¬† #2.¬†Why was Tris shooting her gun? Let alone even touching the "monstrous device". If anybody actually recalls from the book (or movie if you don't read, smh..) Tris shot Will¬† when everybody except The Divergent were under the attack simulation in Abnegation. In the book it goes into a lot of detail what she was feeling in that moment and how she just killed one of her best friends. In the book she couldn't pick up a gun because it reminded her too much of what she did to Will. She was traumatized. And now all of the sudden she has no freaking problem killing 30 people in 10 seconds. No thought of Will, no regrets, no flashbacks.....  #3.¬†Anybody else notice that the factionless looked ON POINT (on fleek if you will). They are supposed to look like a rugged not fed homeless living in a box tattered clothed person. Now all of the sudden they have extremely great weapons and leather jackets to match?? You've GOT to be kidding me!  #4. Did that thing with her mom happen in the book cause I don't remember it at all! I'm pretty sure that's just a fear landscape or maybe just a really scary thought of how her mom has passed and now dead. I have no clue.......      ...................................................and I was just getting started............................................................................. ¬†

If you haven't seen the movie and Tris isn't shooting a gun, some people will be thinking "Ugh typical teenage girl. What a chicken, soooo not gonna see the movie." The whole book is basically half talk and traveling and quarter action and killing people. The other quarter is me and probably Tobias wanting to beat the shit out of Tris. Most of us, if we looked it up on YouTube, obviously are interested in it. You are allowed to state what you think about it, just don't go and attack other people for expressing their own thoughts! My opinion is that the trailer is a little misleading and doesn't appear to follow the plot of the book, but trailers never give you the whole movie, for all we know, the movie could be spectacular! Yes, it's going to be a tad bit different, but we should all expect it. I mean, it's an adaptation, not a copy. The people who wrote the movie are only doing their job. They are trying to keep a large audience of people who watched the first movie and another large audience of people who read the books entertained. We should all just be happy that they even decided to make a movie adaptation of the book in the first place. I mean, movies cost thousands of dollars to make. The actors and actresses didn't have to show up everyday for months and take shot after shot of the same scene for days strait. The directors and script writers didn't have to pay the money to even produce the movie. Just be glad the people involved in the movie's production even considered creating it. And anyway, it's just a two hour movie. Watching it is only going to take two hours out of your life, and if you're disappointed, you're disappointed. Life goes on. So, will you stop biting each others heads off! Everyone is going to see the trailer with different eyes! ¬†¬†¬†

text: What the hell did I just watch? BECAUSE IT WASNT ANYTHING TO DO WITH INSURGENT!  Tris can't even shoot a gun until the end of insurgent (and even then she can barely do it) and she used a gun MULTIPLE TIMES during this 3 minute period.   Why did they have to include a SEXUAL SCENE? None of that happens! The furthest it gets is Tris' shirt getting pulled up a bit.  WHY IS TRIS TALKING TO CALEB ABOUT A BOX AND WHY WAS THERE A BOX? THERE WAS NOTHING ABOUT A BOX IN THE BOOKS! On a file, on Jeanine's computer in her HEAVILY GUARDED LAB, yeah.   The simulation of Tris seeing her Mum was completely wrong, because according to the produces of Insurgent, standing on a bus with your Mum is the exact same as jumping off a building to grab hold of a burning floating house.   Why did they make the faction less heavily guarded? Because they aren't. They're just people who are mainly divergents that want to fight back.   Where's the tension between Tobias and Tris?   What the hell were those snaky-wirery-things that we're going into Tris?   What the hell, Hollywood? I know people will say that they're just making it more interesting etc but it would be nice to see them make a film actually like the book, without needing to change most of the plot. You've done it with The Hunger Games, Harry Potter, Percy Jackson, LOTR... But no. You've gone one fandom too far this time.

text: It's sad to say this but I really didn't like the first movie. Didn't hate it, but disliked it. It was very disappointing and didn't do justice to the book and as a film in general. I like actors such as Shailene Woodley, Ansel Elgort and Miles Teller and they were good as Tris, Caleb, and Peter, but I didn't like Theo James as Four/Tobias. In the books, I found Four really fascinating as a character, but James' acting was very wooden and boring which distracted me. I love Kate Winslet, but she doesn't fit as Jeanine IMO. I pictured someone like Meryl Streep as the antagonist just like how she appeared in The Giver. The fact that Al's suicide was just glanced over quickly irritated me. It did affect Tris heavily because of how the faction system can affect a person like him who just felt very overwhelmed by what it did to him.  I have read all three of the books and liked them, with Insurgent being my favorite out of the three. I am going to re-read the series again in the future. This trailer doesn't impress me like the first one did. Also, I hated that Edward was not in the first movie since he plays an important part in the second book (at least in the beginning) when Tris and Four meet him again in the train to Amity since he became factionless. That was after he got stabbed in the eye and had to be sent back. It showed how much brutality was brought onto a former Dauntless and what the faction system can do to someone. How does that happen? I don't know.

text: Ok. What I'm about to say will offend some people but it's my opinion as a fangirl and writer.¬† First off that trailer. Two words: Shit and promising. For a book based movie, it's shit. For a movie, promising.¬† Look, I've read all three of the books. I'm really pissed off at all the fangirls screaming about how perfect they were. The books were okay. Nothing more, nothing less. The writing as you keep going in the trilogy gets worst. Veronica starts trying too hard. So, Insurgent the book was bad (not awful just bad).¬† I understand the screenwriter's choice to deviate from the book. The screenwriter tried to improve it. Now, I am pissed off about this box because (SPOILER ALERT) it makes no sense. In the books, it was a computer (I think) and it contained a file that revealed the truth about the city and what was going on outside it.¬† Also, Jeanine studied Tris's brain, not hooked her up to some cables and put her in another simulation. T  The first movie was horrible and ruined a half-decent book. As a movie (not an adaptation) this looks like an attempt at a step up. About the love triangle, I personally think having any love in this book and movie ruins it. Tris is a half-decent protagonist that was ruined by being attached to a love interest. I think the book would've been improved if Veronica had chosen one story: either Tris or Four.¬†  I know this trailer for an adaptation looks awful. Understand, this book wasn't The Giver. It wasn't good in the first place. I actually applaud the director and screenwriter on trying to improve it.¬†

text: When something is adapted to screen it isn't going to be the same as reading the book. Blockbuster movies with a sizeable budget and scale have to be profitable, and reach the widest audience possible to be a success and unfortunately that doesn't always include the "original" rabid fans of the source material.  If you really love a book, then love that book, hold on to how you pictured the story and think of the movies as a separate entity, otherwise your attitude will almost guaranteed ¬†your disappointment. This way you might be able to salvage coming off self righteous and whiny when you cram your original fan diatribe down peoples throats.  Veronica Roth sold the rights, and is very very loosely involved in the films. If you want to be mad at someone blame her.

text: Yes, there are some changes, but from what I saw in the trailer I think the director is staying true to the book believe it or not because as I was reading the book I imagined the whole movie in my head chapter by chapter, and what I see is pretty much what I saw in my head. If every detail in the book was put in the movie it would be predictable to almost everyone who has read the series, so in my opinion it's nice to see some changes cause then you're like wow that's was pretty awesome to have see it done like that. I'm excited to finally see more of the characters from Insurgent like Evelyn, Uriah, Johanna, Marlene, Lynn, Jack Kang, Hector, and Edgar. Every director is different with vision, and he's done movies like The Time Travelers Wife from RED so which is where I think the action pack in this movie came from hahaha. Just remember Divegent fandom, we made this series into what it is now, and it's very hard for a series of books to be amazing after the first movie because of how it's presented in film. Harry Potter, Twilight, The Hunger Games, Divergent and The Maze Runner have been truly the most successful franchises within young adults. But for some series that didn't do well that I had high hopes for like, Beautiful Creatures, The Mortal Instruments, and Vampire Academy, I wish they would continue these ones but with different directors but that's not up to me is it. Just be glad Divergent made it through the harshness of young critiques. Either way, I can't wait for March 20! MIDNIGHT PREMIER FOR ME :)

text: First, I have to comment on everyone mentioning that most movies adapted from books almost always have plot changes, because they are correct. That happened with the Bourne movies (of which the last one wasn't even written by the original author, but that's the subject of another thread). The entire raison d'√™tre of the Jason Bourne books...yes, the entire backbone of the story was removed to simplify the movie for the screen. It's a very involved book and it would have been impossible to include it all so they went for a basic story line to support an action movie. I'm not a fan of the movies mostly because Matt Damon, as great of an actor as he is, is not Jason Bourne. The fact that a book I loved was deprived of its backbone doesn't bother me as much as the casting because I look at the book and movie as apples and oranges. They are similar but different. Anyway, my husband did not read the books and LOVES the movies. This is just how it goes. I accept it and try to deal with it lol. On a side note, Renner would have made a perfect Bourne based on the book (rugged, tough, but still nice looking and someone who you might see and in the next thought completely forget. This guy was a badass killer spy after all).   As far as Insurgent goes...I just finished reading the book (I found the series from the first movie) and I am looking forward to seeing the movie. I love the cast and I can see the connections from the book to the trailer. As many have said the box is probably an adaptation of the video, the box/house flying through the air is in a simulation and obviously there to bring more excitement to a book that is a bit slower paced/thoughtful. And Tris' hair is cut really short anyway so I don't get the fuss. Do I love a pixie cut on her? Not my favorite, but I don't care about that as much as I care about quality acting. I'm going to enjoy this for what it is, a fresh (and by fresh, I mean new) take on a book I really enjoyed reading. I get the people that are pissed off...I mentioned the Bourne issue because I was ticked off about it for a while because I was invested in that book series...but, it'll gets easier with time everyone ;)

text: First, There is nothing wrong classifying Insurgent as an action movie, since the books are obviously filled with action sequences. It's not a drama, not a romantic movie, nor a comedy. There's no such genre as "Young-Adult Dystopia", so "Action" or even "Science Fiction" are totally appropriate. Get your "facts" straight. Secondly, the producers obviously have read the books since they were the ones who decided: Hey, this book (Divergent) has potential to become a movie. So, clearly they read it, liked it and decided to adapt it. This word is important: ADAPT. They have to modify things to match and rise the general public expectations, the fandom represents 5% or less of the audience. Movies and books work differently, and in Insurgent they have five hundreds of pages to show in nearly a two-hour-long movie. What is important will be portrayed and what is irrelevant (such as the appearance of a hard drive or the colors of Amity's clothes) will be cut. They have already proved that Insurgent will seem way more mature than Divergent, as Insurgent book is also more mature than Divergent. I know that almost everyone who is complaining the fuck out of the changes will see the movie and be like: OMG, that's so awesome. Or I LOVED IT. Just like what happened to Divergent movie changes. I'll be here watching who's complaining now and witness in March those same people praising about it.

text: Most normal people will watch this and think "WHOA SO EXCITING AND INTENSE!" Me? I just finished reading the Divergent series. This trailer does excite me, but it makes me cry.  Everyone whos read the series will understand why. (Unintentional Rhyme) I can't look at -the specific character- (Im sure you know who Im talking about) without welling up with tears.  Hats off to Veronica Roth. She sure knows how to emotionally affect her readers for days and days after they've finished the books. So much so they can't watch Divergent, or this trailer without crying. Warning to those who haven't read the series yet, you can either go without reading and have the whole thing be an insane surprise, or find out and still be extremely emotional with more of an emotional connection with the characters.  I feel like I 'know' the characters and with what happened to one of them, I feel like it actually happened to a friend. Its an insane experience I do think people should share with me. Read the books. I promise, it will be worth it, and you can virtually rip me a new one once you've read the last book, Allegiant, if you feel that to be necessary for me making you go through that. text: Didn't read the books... didn't give a damn to really, and probably won't even still after. Really wasn't keen on the first movie til I watched it a third time. This trailer is super action packed. I'm juked to see it.   I wish randoms would understand..., some people just don't get off on books like they do, or maybe they just prefer different genres of reading. Like me... I can read trashing romance novels all day long, but I hate watching people on screen get it on for more than 3 secs makes my stomach turn.      Action (Science fiction) books... I prefer see it all on screen! I get juiced to watch it all lay out in front of my eyes. I don't want to imagine it. It's so boring on paper to me. I dont make it past the first 2 pages typically.   Unfortunately, with films they can't fit it all in when there is a movie... so you gotta piece it together. Which means your favorite bits may be missing. Grow up kids, and move on. We all know that's how it works.  Let's just be happy that our favorite books are coming to life and there are other people in the world who like them just as much as us that you made a movie happen!

Now, this is what I do......   Watch the FIRST movie.  Read about the ENTIRE series on Wiki  THEN read the FIRST book and see if I like it, or see if I can even READ it.¬† both Twilight AND Harry Potter were pretty shitty books in my opinion and I could not make it through the first few chapters of either, despite having seen the movies.¬† BUT, I loved the movies.¬† Other books like E.T. and Firestarter, I never would have been able to read through had I not seen the movies.

The Lord of the rings/ the hobbit trilogy's were not consistent with the books, The Hunger games movie were not consistent with the books, hell even the VERY first jurassic park wasn't consistent with the book  But here's the thing. Even though they weren't based exactly on the source material in their entirety, they still entertain people and they still established major fanbases! Why ? Because the movies were good and were amazing! Even though they were different from the source material ( regardless of what you say about the hobbit, I talked to a good amount of people that said they enjoyed it and if you think that they don't know what they're talking about then I feel sad for you )  All I'm saying is for all of you to watch it as a movie! and review and judge it fairly as a movie. text: I saw this last night. I like this better than the 1st film. From Tobias and Tris alone, guilt, shame, grief, fear, anger, hatred and revenge be it internal or external some up Insurgent's personality. Tobias still unable to find forgiveness for his fathers abuse and his mothers abandonment while Tris's torture over her parents death and having to kill a fellow dauntless friend who was under Jeanines control. Plus she has a cowardly brother, Caleb who simply isn't built for war and would defect when given the chance. Her self loathing and anger jeanine was compelling to watch until she found her inner peace in the simulation unit. I almost didn't recognise Naomi Watts as Evelyn, the leader of the factionless revolution who's an undercurrent of pent up rage be it at her ex husband or Jeanine herself. Jeanine is the soul definition of the phrase by any means necessary. Dealing with the fact that she would sanction multiple killings(men, women & children) without a second thought to achieve her objectives(seeking the faction box and fleshing out the strongest divergent) or what she believes is the greater good. Insurgent really raise the stakes yet it feels like only half the battle.Ôªø

text: Just watched Insurgent a few hours ago. Here's what I found most importantly different. WARNING: Spoilers. Duh.   The entire meaning of Insurgent was taken out of the movie. Insurgent: adjective. "rising in active revolt". This was taken from the part of the book when Tris, Christina, and Marcus teamed up together, correct? Yes. HOWEVER, in the movie, they did NOT team up. (I did not realize this until after the movie was over.) Also, Cara (Will's sister) was no where to be found. Max was not killed by Lynn and Lynn was not shot and confessed she liked Marlene before she died. So, Max and Lynn both didn't die in the movie.  Let's back up a few paces here. Remember in the book how Eric was put on trial in Candor by the Dauntless Loyals? That didn't happen in the movie. After Eric almost shot the little girl but Tris jumped on him, he took her and put handcuffs on her. Action happened, lalalala, etc., then guns are all pointed on Eric and the other Dauntless Traitors. After Eric says "I learned how to live with the blood on my hands. But can you?" Four shoots him without warning. In the book, Four whispers, "Be brave, Eric." before killing him. I really missed this aspect because it shows how hesitant Four was to shooting Eric. I thought I was going to be more upset about this part in the movie because Jai Courtney is hot as hell, but because it was filmed differently, I don't know how to feel.  This might be very important for all of you guys, too: That "piercing" on Tris's shoulder blade is not actually a piercing. It is a little bullet from the Dauntless Traitors attack, when they were searching for Divergents. Remember? This was actually pretty accurate because Tris's shoulder was hurting and hard to maneuver in the book. ¬†  Backing up to the beginning now. I don't mean to disappoint every single person who read Insurgent or anything, but the scene when Tris ate Amity bread which was intoxicated with "happy serum" or what I believe is marijuana, and was all happy sappy and Four was pissed for Amity making them happy by feeding them bread and all.... Well, this scene is not in the movie. I'm as sad as you are, fangirls and fanboys.¬†  Now let's go to the ending of the story, when Tori kills Jeanine, right? Tori's pissed at Jeanine for killing her Divergent brother, George Wu. According to the movie, we all read the WRONG BOOK. Tori doesn't kill Jeanine? WHAT?! But... that was her revenge at her for "killing" George! That's right, ladies and gents. Instead, in the last moments of the movie, Evelyn goes up behind Jeanine, talking some bullshit, and pulls a gun behind her skull and shoots. FUCK THAT SHIT, RIGHT? I think this is one of scenes I'm mostly angry about.  Ah, what about the sex scene? When I read Insurgent, there were no mentions of sex between Four and Tris and when I read Allegiant there was no obvious sex scenes. But nope, Four and Tris have sex right there and then at Factionless. Sigh. Could this movie get anymore inaccurate?  Another thing that might not be known for those who did not even watch Divergent, but read the entire series is that Caleb's girly friend is no where mentioned. That's right. No Susan anywhere.¬†  One last rant, okay? So recall that back in Amity when the Dauntless Traitors evaded the cafeteria and were shooting everywhere, Tris pushed Peter away from getting killed? Well that wasn't in the movie either, my dearest friends! Instead, while Jeanine, Caleb, and Peter were watching Tris's simulation, Tris had the chance to shoot Peter in her simulation. She didn't do it though, because of her inner Stiff. Also, earlier when Tris had just arrived for her simulation, she was beating up Peter and threatened to Jeanine that if she didn't stop the suicides, then she would kill Peter. Jeanine shrug it off, saying how she has other guards. This made Peter feel like Jeanine didn't care about him and that Tris cared about him more than she did. So then lalala later when Tris is being tested after a rest, Peter gives her the serum that makes her appear dead and lalala Peter is a hero yay. But Miles Teller was the perfect Peter, I don't care what anyone says. He's the well-deserved comic relief dude. But all the actors were casted perfectly! At first, before watching Divergent, I cringed at the thought of Theo James being Four. I mean, he's 29 playing an 18-year old? Ha! But I can't imagine Divergent without him being Four.  Thanks for reading if you've come this far! Hopefully I helped you understand what happened in the movie if you are unable to go see it yourself. Apologies for this being so long but it was necessary. I still loved Insurgent despite that extreme differences. So action-packed! My heart was racing so many times during the film and I jumped and gasped and it was just a great experience nonetheless.

text: Movies are turning into soaps/TV nonsense these days.. SIGH ...  If it's not Hunger games, it's Underworld or this Divergent series and even Star Wars/Alien or LOTR. Movies are unwatchable these days and I can't identify whit them. It won't be long till we have the normal soapie nonsense my wife yearns so much for- memory loss, people dying then coming back to life in a following installment, illegitimate children who turn up form nowhere, childbirth scenes all over the place and just a lot of redundant talk about nonsense and "feelings".. rinse/repeat  I saw the first Divergent and it was good enough. That should have been it. The rest- I couldn't get into. Same with Star Wars- the first 3 were great, the rest I have not seen, coz they're unnecessary and they try to milk every ounce of a good trilogy. Haven't seen Hunger Games, coz I just can't get into it(I always lose interest a few minutes in)- seen the first Underworld.  Where are the days where you just got a great movie and it ends there? Perhaps ONE sequel with a totally different premise and team?
